I can rescue the dying and heal the wounded.”

69
00:03:00,220 --> 00:03:02,400
Uh...Ok.

70
00:03:02,400 --> 00:03:06,560
So why else are you in Red Army school?

71
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:08,860
"I want to know our past.”

72
00:03:08,860 --> 00:03:10,811
I think there are a few things that little

73
00:03:10,821 --> 00:03:11,821
Susie here

74
00:03:11,821 --> 00:03:13,950
might not be learning about her past.

75
00:03:13,950 --> 00:03:17,060
You see the Red Army was established in the
1920’s—

76
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:19,680
a guerilla Communist army dedicated to

77
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:21,719
overthrowing the government,

78
00:03:21,719 --> 00:03:23,069
and stealing everyone’s stuff

79
00:03:23,069 --> 00:03:26,499
so they could redistribute it as they saw
fit.

80
00:03:26,499 --> 00:03:29,209
Now obviously that didn’t sound too appealing

81
00:03:29,209 --> 00:03:30,799
to a lot of people,

82
00:03:30,799 --> 00:03:33,919
so the Red Army came up with a compromise—

83
00:03:33,919 --> 00:03:35,900
kill anyone who disagrees.

84
00:03:35,900 --> 00:03:38,189
After being nearly defeated by the forces

85
00:03:38,189 --> 00:03:40,650
of the previous government of China,

86
00:03:40,650 --> 00:03:43,470
the Red Army embarked on one of the most glorious

87
00:03:43,470 --> 00:03:45,459
and proudly remembered moments

88
00:03:45,459 --> 00:03:47,629
in the Chinese Regime’s history—

89
00:03:47,629 --> 00:03:49,839
The Long March.

90
00:03:49,839 --> 00:03:51,079
What a victory!

91
00:03:51,079 --> 00:03:53,489
More than 80,000 people started,

92
00:03:53,489 --> 00:03:56,059
and only 6,000 made it to the end,

93
00:03:56,059 --> 00:03:58,430
with tens of thousands of soldiers dying

94
00:03:58,430 --> 00:04:00,439
or deserting along the way.

95
00:04:00,439 --> 00:04:02,370
Everyone looked so happy.

96
00:04:02,370 --> 00:04:06,010
Finally, the CCP set up camp in Yan’an.

97
00:04:06,010 --> 00:04:08,400
And boy did their Red Army get busy!

98
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:12,920
The CCP treated Yan’an as a revolutionary
holy land,

99
00:04:12,920 --> 00:04:16,759
a place where they cleansed people’s minds
of terrible,

100
00:04:16,759 --> 00:04:18,079
dangerous things—

101
00:04:18,079 --> 00:04:22,759
like morality, independent thought, and human
dignity.

102
00:04:22,759 --> 00:04:24,590
You might call it brainwashing.

103
00:04:24,590 --> 00:04:28,400
The CCP at the time called it purging human
nature.

104
00:04:28,400 --> 00:04:31,539
Ironically, when Little Susie said she wanted
to

105
00:04:31,539 --> 00:04:34,150
"rescue the dying and heal the wounded"

106
00:04:34,150 --> 00:04:37,840
that was actually part of a slogan Mao used
in Yan’an,

107
00:04:37,840 --> 00:04:39,220
when he said that medical workers

108
00:04:39,220 --> 00:04:43,060
should practice “revolutionary humanitarianism.”

109
00:04:43,060 --> 00:04:44,460
Right.

110
00:04:44,460 --> 00:04:48,240
Well, the Red Army’s “revolutionary humanitarianism”

111
00:04:48,250 --> 00:04:50,050
included forced confessions,

112
00:04:50,050 --> 00:04:51,650
self-criticism sessions,

113
00:04:51,650 --> 00:04:53,000
and something called douzheng,

114
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,690
a term for a particular type of struggle.

115
00:04:56,690 --> 00:05:00,110
And if a person resisted having his thoughts
cleansed,

116
00:05:00,110 --> 00:05:02,180
he would often be tortured,

117
00:05:02,180 --> 00:05:03,259
or beheaded,

118
00:05:03,259 --> 00:05:05,889
or hacked to death with axes.

119
00:05:05,889 --> 00:05:09,539
The Red Army killed 10,000 people in Yan’an,

120
00:05:09,539 --> 00:05:11,900
including many of its own soldiers.

121
00:05:11,900 --> 00:05:14,669
So yeah, kids these days really don’t appreciate

122
00:05:14,669 --> 00:05:16,990
what it was like to be in the Red Army back
then.

123
00:05:16,990 --> 00:05:19,569
But that’s probably not what Little Susie

124
00:05:19,569 --> 00:05:22,289
is learning about the Red Army.

125
00:05:22,289 --> 00:05:24,939
Because the CCP has a way of rewriting,

126
00:05:24,939 --> 00:05:28,669
or shall we say “glorifying” history.

127
00:05:28,669 --> 00:05:30,780
This China Central Television special called

128
00:05:30,780 --> 00:05:34,520
“Ode to Yan’an” is a good example.

129
00:05:34,520 --> 00:05:37,879
Look at these glorious soldiers on the Long
March!

130
00:05:37,879 --> 00:05:43,699
And here’s Chairman Mao giving a fellow
revolutionary his coat!

131
00:05:43,699 --> 00:05:47,779
I wish I could have been a revolutionary Red
Army soldier back then!

132
00:05:47,780 --> 00:05:48,439
Weird, though:

133
00:05:48,439 --> 00:05:49,900
State-run media left out the parts

134
00:05:49,900 --> 00:05:52,700
about torturing and brainwashing.

135
00:05:52,700 --> 00:05:55,680
So, yes, kids should be educated

136
00:05:55,689 --> 00:05:58,550
about the CCP’s Red Army.

137
00:05:58,550 --> 00:06:00,009
But if history repeats itself,

138
00:06:00,009 --> 00:06:02,930
it might be good if these kids were also taught

139
00:06:02,930 --> 00:06:05,729
about the tragic parts of China’s history—

140
